Add a PSR-3 style logging system that should be compatible with PHP 5.2+.More information on PSR-3 here: https://github.com/php-fig/fig-standards/blob/master/accepted/PSR-3-logger-interface.mdnnThis logging system roughly complies with the requirements for PSR-3, but doesnnot actually extend/implement/reuse any of the PSR namespaces, classes orninterfaces. This decision was made in an effort to maintain compatibility withnPHP 5.2+ and to be consistent with the current style of this library.nnFour new logging classes are available out of the box:nn 1. Google_Logger_Abstract: This abstract class implements most of thenfunctionality required for a logger. The only detail that is left to thenconcrete classes is the `write()` method. If you want to create a customnlogger, you should extend this class.nn 2. Google_Logger_Null: This logger simply discards all messages. You can usenthis logger to ensure that no messages will be logged. This is the defaultnlogger.nn 3. Google_Logger_File: This logger will write messages to just about anynwritable stream resource you give it.nn 4. Google_Logger_Psr: This logger exists to allow for interoperability withnother PSR-3 logging systems. All you need to do is provide this loggernwith and instance of another logger and you're done. Below is annexample of integrating with Monolog:nn~~~phpnuse MonologLogger;nuse MonologHandlerStreamHandler;nn$monolog = new Logger('Google API');n$monolog->pushHandler(new StreamHandler('php://output', Logger::INFO));nn$config = new Google_Config();n$config->setLoggerClass('Google_Logger_Psr');nn$client = new Google_Client($config);n$client->getLogger()->setLogger($monolog);nn// Logs: [2014-11-16 16:28:21] Google API.INFO: Service Call {service:books...n$service = new Google_Service_Books($client);n$service->volumes->listVolumes('Henry David Thoreau');nn// Logs: [2014-11-16 16:28:21] Google API.ERROR: My custom errorn$client->getLogger()->error('My custom error');n~~~n

Add support for retrying failed requests with exponential backoff.This feature can be enabled by setting the `retries` configuration for then`Google_Task_Runner` class:nn~~~phpn$client = new Google_Client();n$client->setClassConfig('Google_Task_Runner', 'retries', 5);n~~~nnOnce `retries` is configured, the following error types will be retried byndefault:nn * Errors with a `500` or a `503` HTTP status code.n * Errors with a `rateLimitExceeded` or a `userRateLimitExceeded` reason type.n * cURL errors:n   * `CURLE_COULDNT_RESOLVE_HOST`n   * `CURLE_COULDNT_CONNECT`n   * `CURLE_OPERATION_TIMEOUTED`n   * `CURLE_SSL_CONNECT_ERROR`n   * `CURLE_GOT_NOTHING`nnThese error types can be configured using the `retry_map` configurations fornthe `Google_IO_Exception` and `Google_Service_Exception` classes. The retry mapnis an associative array which maps errors types to the number of times eachnerror can be retried (-1 can be used to retry an error indefinitely). Fornexample:nn~~~phpn$client = new Google_Client();n$client->setClassConfig(n'Google_Service_Exception',n'retry_map',narray(n// Don't retry 500 errorsn'500' => 0,n// Retry 503 errors oncen'503' => 1,n// Retry rate limit errors until we hit `retries`n'rateLimitExceeded' => -1,n'userRateLimitExceeded' => -1n)n);n~~~nnFor convenience, `Google_Config` provides three constants for configuring retrynlimits: `Google_Config::TASK_RETRY_NEVER`, `Google_Config::TASK_RETRY_ONCE`, andn`Google_Config::TASK_RETRY_ALWAYS`.n

Tame redundant tests.All 18 test classes that extend `BaseTest` inherit the same two tests. A sideneffect of this is that more than half of the assertions reported by PHPUnitnare from the same two test methods running over and over again.nnI've refactored these test methods to live in more appropriate test classes.nI've also updated the `testIncludes` method to:nn * Use a data provider so all failures will be printed at once.n * Give a nice error message instead of triggering a fatal error.n * Use the autoloader since that's the preferred method for including classes.n
